<br>
Lotteries are generally run by &quot;the state&quot; or some other charitable organization.  Here in Canada we have lotteries organized by hospitals or the Cancer Society (for example) where tickets are $100 each, but you have a 1 in 15 chance of winning a prize.  The prizes are either houses, cars, cash or minor prizes worth at least $250.  In those cases, you know the proceeds are going to a worthwhile cause, which (IMO) makes participating in such a lottery acceptable and winnings would not be &quot;dirty&quot;.<br>
<br>
In the case of &quot;state&quot; lotteries, most people see it as a form of voluntary taxation.  The revenue from the lottery sales goes into the government's budget to be used for health care, education, infrastructure, etc.  People are voluntarily giving money to the government, but with a chance to win something back (If only income tax worked that way <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ).<br>
<br>
The next thing you can have (at least this is the case in Ontario) are state run casinos.  Similar concept to lotteries, some people see them as voluntary taxation as the profits (gambler's losses) go into the government's budget for use just like lottery proceeds.  Unfortunatley, casinos are much more likely to lead someone to a gambling addiction than a lottery, so in some sense I do see &quot;state&quot; casino winnings as &quot;dirty money&quot;.<br>
<br>
Finally, you have the casinos that are like the ones in Vegas.  Privately owned, where the proceeds (read gambler's losses again) go entirely to the profit of the company.  Since no real good comes out of the money that gambler's lose I usually regard any winnings from a private casino as &quot;dirty money&quot;.  There is no mitigating factor in the trasaction to even remotely make the situation palatable.<br>
<br>
I hope that made sense.  Oh, and just as an aside, lottery winnings in Canada are tax free. <p>Christians know that it is not possible to reject or ignore God without demeaning man<br>
