BINGO!! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Spent less money than going out to eat or watching a movie, had a couple of hours with my girlfriend talking, while blotting numbers.  I did it for enjoyment.  Bingo is big business here in Kentucky, most of the Bingo's are church or charity organized.<br>
I don't see a difference between that and playing the lottery.  If I'm going to spend on it, it's for a chance to win but I'm not expecting to win.  Also, here in Kentucky, lottery proceeds are supposed to go to education, although I don't know how or where to find out how the proceeds are spent.  It's also like anything else, if it becomes an addiction in any way, it's trouble.  All things in moderation right?<br>
<br>
I remember the interview they did on Jack, when he won the lottery, seemed like a really nice man.  He had a reputation for taking care of his workers if I remember the interview correctly, so him contributing to churches just seems to follow from what he would normally do.  Like having a windfall placed in his lap from many jobs and extra money to contribute to causes he thinks are worthy.  <br>
<br>
Churches accepting money, I've not heard of one declining money?  And even if the money was ill-gotten, say from drug runners and so forth (which would seem strange to me that someone who was into those types of things would contribute to a church?), all it amounts to is cash that can be spent to help those in the church or community?  How would accepting cash or donations necessarily be condoning how the person came to have the money to contribute?  So unless the contribution was a way to gain influence (which is wrong anyway) or to control the church itself (which is also wrong), why/how would it be a problem?<br>
<br>
God bless,<br>
Von<br>
